The Park had not been surveyed previously for mosquitoes, but 32 species are known from adjacent Knox County (
Hribar & Gerhardt 1986
). Species such as
Oc. japonicus (Theobald)
have recently invaded the USA and could move into the natural rock­pool habitats in the Park (
Peyton et al. 1999
;
Scott et al. 2001
).

Ochlerotatus triseriatus
is potentially the most significant human­biting mosquito in the Park. Although it is not always the dominant human biter, it is present throughout most of the year. It is also the primary vector of LaCrosse encephalitis virus (
Nasci et al. 2000
), a potentially serious arbovirus. LaCrosse encephalitis is endemic in Cherokee, NC and Cosby, TN (
Anonymous 1990
;
Gottfried et al. 2002
), and thus is in the Park.
Barnard & Durden ( 2000 )
noted that this mosquito feeds on reptiles.
